This is the source code to the TOURNAMENT TRIVIA win32 BBS doorgame.

v1.0 original game release: July 2003

Released as freeware and open source (GPL3), October 2010.

Directories:

/release
    Contains the contents of the original Tournament Trivia 1.0 zip release.
    For a general README on the game, see release/readme.txt
    
/source/trivia
    Source for Tournament Trivia. Apologies for the awful tab-stops and odd
    indentation. 3-space tabs? Aligning braces with their bodies? Good lord.
    Please fork this and reformat!

/source/intrnode
    Source for "ObjectDoor" door engine -- see below.
    Same horrible indentation practices as the trivia source, I'm afraid :)

/keygen
    Contains a keygen exe and its source


About Tournament Trivia:

Players compete  with each other in real-time, trying to be the first to answer
the current question.  Scores add up from day to day, and are reset at the end
of the month, with one player emerging victorious. Excellent multi-node support
that also functions as a chat room.  

Runs on Synchronet, as well as any Windows-based BBS software that supports
DOOR32.SYS (Winserver, Mystic, EleBBS, and GameSrv)



About ObjectDoor:

This is an engine I wrote for building Win32 multiuser doorgames.  It makes
multiuser BBS games substantially easier to write by passing all major game
functionality to a background process, which is communicated with via Win32
Mailslots for its IPC mechanism.  It uses multithreading extensively.

It can build executables for either the Synchronet XSDK or the OpenDoors 
doorkit -- link the appropriate one in when compiling.

In 2003-04 I started work on a version of Intrnode that builds a single
executable supporting both doorkits, and I also started Linux and FreeBSD
ports of the software.  Neither were completed, but if I can dig them up,
I'll release them as a branch.



Compiling:

All code was originally compiled on Borland C++ 5.  With modern compilers, YMMV.


## Linux Port

Tournament Trivia was originally written as a 32-bit Windows application. The source code has been updated to compile and run on Linux (64-bit) while maintaining full binary compatibility with the original Windows data file formats (e.g., `settings.dat`, `player.dat`). Claude AI was used to port the code to Linux.

### Key Changes by File

| File | Changes |
|------|---------|
| `platformDefs.h` | POSIX mqueue types (`mqd_t`), `std::recursive_mutex` for critical sections, MQ constants, guarded `HANDLE`/`INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE` redefinitions |
| `intrnode.cpp` | Rewrote IPC using `mq_open`/`mq_send`/`mq_receive` instead of Windows mailslots |
| `gamesrv.cpp` | Fixed critical sections (lock/unlock), thread launch bug, `std::terminate` removal, `mq_getattr`/`mq_receive` in run loop, `std::filesystem` fixes |
| `door.cpp` | Rewrote `getOutput()` with mqueue, proper cleanup in `beforeExit()`, removed debug prints |
| `door.h` | Added Linux platform detection (`XSDK32`/`OD32`), guarded color constants against `__COLORS` enum conflict |
| `linuxPlatformDefs.cpp` | Fixed `strcmpi()` null terminator bug |
| `Makefile` | Added `-D__CONSOLE__`, `-lrt`, `-lpthread` flags |

### Debug Logging

To enable logging, create an empty file called `debug.on` in the Tournament Trivia directory (where the executable is). Logs will be written to `trivsrv.log`.

### SDKs and Libraries

The game uses the following SDKs/libraries:

- **OpenDoors SDK** -- Used by the `triv32` Door32-compatible executable for BBS door I/O
- **XSDK (Synchronet External Program SDK)** -- Used by `trivsync` for native Synchronet BBS integration
- **ncurses** -- Used by the `trivconfig` configuration utility for its text-based UI
- **POSIX message queues** -- Replace Windows mailslots for inter-process communication between the game server (`trivsrv`) and client processes (`trivsync`/`triv32`)

## Building on Linux

All build targets are managed by the Makefile in the `updated/trivia/` directory.

### Prerequisites

- GCC / G++ with C++20 support
- ncurses development library (`libncurses-dev` or `ncurses-devel`)
- POSIX real-time library (`librt`, typically included with glibc)
- pthreads (`libpthread`, typically included with glibc)
- OpenDoors library (pre-built in the Synchronet source tree; the Makefile expects `SBBS_REPO_ROOT` to point to a Synchronet repository checkout)

### Build Commands

From the `updated/trivia/` directory:

```bash
# Build all targets
make

# Build individual targets
make trivsrv       # Game server (manages game state, rounds, scoring)
make trivsync      # Synchronet client (connects player to trivsrv via XSDK)
make triv32        # Door32 / OpenDoors client
make trivconfig    # Configuration program (ncurses TUI for editing settings.dat)
make regtriv       # Registration key generator

# Clean all build artifacts
make clean
```

### Makefile Configuration

The Makefile expects `ODOORS_SRC` to be set to the path of the OpenDoors SDK library and XSDK headers. The OpenDoors library is
assumed to be already built.  For instance, for Synchronet, with the Synchronet Git repository cloned, ODOORS_SRC would be
something like /sbbs/repo/src/odoors


```makefile
ODOORS_SRC = /sbbs/repo/src/odoors
```

## Programs

### trivsrv -- Game Server

The game server process that manages all game state: player tracking, question rounds, scoring, clue timing, and chat. It communicates with one or more client processes (`trivsync` or `triv32`) via POSIX message queues. One `trivsrv` instance runs per active game session.

### trivsync -- Synchronet Client

The Synchronet-specific client executable. It uses Synchronet's XTRN.DAT drop file and the XSDK for terminal I/O, providing support for Synchronet global commands such as online user lists, logon/logoff notifications, and inter-node paging.

### triv32 -- Door32 / OpenDoors Client

The Door32-compatible client executable, built with the OpenDoors SDK. It reads a DOOR32.SYS drop file and works with any BBS software that supports Door32 doors.

### trivconfig -- Configuration Program

A standalone ncurses-based text user interface for editing the game's `settings.dat` configuration file. It reads and writes the exact same 290-byte binary format used by the original 32-bit Windows game, ensuring full compatibility.

Settings that can be configured:

| Setting | Description | Range | Default |
|---------|-------------|-------|---------|
| Question Frequency | How long an unanswered question remains before being replaced | 25-75 seconds | 50 |
| Max Clues | Maximum number of clues displayed per question | 0-4 | 3 |
| Player Inactivity Timeout | Time before an idle player is disconnected | 60-600 seconds | 300 |
| Show Sysops on Score List | Whether sysop players appear on the score list | Yes/No | Yes |
| Verify Question Submissions | Whether custom question submissions require approval | Yes/No | Yes |
| Question Files (1-10) | Filenames of trivia question databases to load | Up to 10 files | database.enc, custom.txt |
| Previous Month's Winner | Display name of last month's winner (informational) | Text | none |
| Previous Month's High Score | Last month's winning score (informational) | 0-32767 | 0 |

**Usage:**
```bash
cd /path/to/trivia    # Must run from the directory containing settings.dat
./trivconfig
```

**Controls:**
- Up/Down arrows (or `j`/`k`): Navigate menu items
- Enter: Edit selected item
- Space: Toggle Yes/No items
- `Q`: Quit (prompts to save if changes were made)

### regtriv -- Registration Key Generator

A console utility that generates registration key files (`ttreg.dat`) for Tournament Trivia. It prompts for a sysop name and produces an encoded key file, then verifies the key by decoding it back.

Source: `updated/keygen/regtriv.cpp`

**Usage:**
```bash
./regtriv
```

The program creates `ttreg.dat` (the registration key) and appends a log entry to `regs.log` in the current directory.

## Setup

### Synchronet BBS

To add Tournament Trivia to a Synchronet BBS, configure an external program in SCFG:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| Name | Tournament Trivia |
| Internal Code | TRIVIA |
| Start-up Directory | /path/to/trivia |
| Command Line | trivsync |
| Multiple Concurrent Users | Yes |
| BBS Drop File Type | Synchronet XTRN.DAT |
| Place Drop File In | Node Directory |

When selecting the Synchronet XTRN.DAT drop file type, set "use real names" to "no" for proper alias display in inter-node paging.

### Other BBS Software (Door32)

For BBS software with Door32.sys support, use `triv32` with appropriate command-line options:

```
/D or /DROPFILE  - Door information file directory and/or filename
/N or /NODE      - Sets the node number to use
/SOCKET x        - Needed in EleBBS and GameSrv to specify the socket
/L or /LOCAL     - Operate in local mode (no drop file required)
/USERNAME        - Specify user name in local mode
/SILENT          - No local display window
/GRAPHICS        - Force ANSI mode on
```

## Configuration

Game settings can be changed in two ways:

1. **trivconfig** -- Run the standalone configuration program (recommended)
2. **In-game "config" command** -- Available to sysop users while in the game

## Adding Questions

### Default Question Database

The stock question database is `database.enc`. Updated versions with additional questions may be available from the original distribution site.

In the unregistered version, only 400 questions from `database.enc` are available.

### Custom Questions

Add custom questions to `custom.txt` (or any additional question file configured in settings). The format alternates question and answer lines:

```
What is the capital of France?
Paris
What year did the Berlin Wall fall?
1989
```

Rules:
- Questions are on odd-numbered lines, answers on even-numbered lines
- Press Enter only at the end of each line
- Questions: max 160 characters
- Answers: max 80 characters
- Use a text editor that shows line numbers and has word wrap disabled

Additional question files (up to 10 total) can be added through `trivconfig` or the in-game config command.

In the unregistered version, only 150 total questions from custom/third-party files are available.


